<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> INDONESIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chemical Weapons Treaty Considered </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further Report </H4>
<F P=102> BK0302012594 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0000 GMT 3 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0302012594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Indonesian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Indonesia plans to ratify the Convention on the 
Prohibition of Chemical Weapons by the end of 1994. Hassan 
Wirayuda, director for international organizations in the 
Department of Foreign Affairs, told reporters in Jakarta 
yesterday that the plan will be brought before the House of 
Representatives. This is because deliberations on the matter -- 
which are very delicate and will have a far-reaching impact -- 
will take a long time. 
  Meanwhile, Ian Kenyon, executive director of the 
Organization 
for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, welcomed the Indonesian 
plan. Only four of the 154 countries that signed the convention 
have ratified it. He expressed his hope that more countries 
will ratify the convention. The four countries are Sweden, 
Fiji, Mauritius, and Seychelles. 

</TEXT>

