<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> REGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Report </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2901154394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1341 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2901154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A senior Russian Defence Ministry official believes 
that the Ukrainian military department's latest steps can wreck 
the Russo-American-Ukrainian agreements signed in Moscow on 
January 14. The accords aim at scrapping the nuclear weapons 
deployed in Ukraine. 
  A Russian military spokesman has told Interfax that 
Ukraine's 
Defence Ministry has warned the strategic missile forces 
personnel that the officers refusing to swear allegiance to 
Ukraine will be dismissed. 
  The spokesman described these Ukrainian actions as the start 
of a seizure of strategic nuclear weapons. He stressed that in 
these conditions the Russian military could not bear 
responsibility for the nuclear ammunition's control and service. 
He did not rule out that pressed by Kiev, quite a few missile 
forces officers would have to leave Ukraine with "unpredictable 
consequences." 
  He is convinced that the fate of the nuclear weapons in 
Ukraine must concern primarily Kiev and western countries. "The 
loss of proper control over nuclear weapons may be disastrous," 
he stressed. 

</TEXT>

