<DOCNO> FBIS3-41021 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "jptac001__l94049" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   JPRS-TAC-94-001-L </AU>
Document Type:JPRS 
Document Title:Arms Control 

<DATE1>  22 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> KAZAKHSTAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Adamishin Has `No Official Information' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2801215994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1844 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2801215994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian First Deputy Foreign Minister Anatoliy 
Adamishin told INTERFAX Friday that he had received no official 
information on the statement of the Kazakh ambassador in Tehran 
concerning the republic's intention to decide on the future of 
nuclear weapons on Kazakh territory independently. 
  "Primarily it is necessary to make sure that the information 
is correct and that it reflects the position of the Kazakh 
Government and President Nursultan Nazarbayev," the minister's 
first deputy (who accompanies Russian Premier Viktor 
Chernomyrdin during his official visit to Italy) emphasized. 
  "We have the kind of relations with Kazakhstan which allows 
us to resolve our issues without mediation of ambassadors to 
other states," Adamishin pointed out. 
  The premier's press secretary Anatoliy Sergeyev also 
confirmed that the Russian premier currently in Rome had 
received no official information on the Kazakh ambassador's 
statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

