<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> LATVIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliamentarians Assess U.S. Visit, Russian Troop Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0302180594 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1400 GMT 3 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0302180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A delegation from the Latvian Saeima, consisting of 
representatives of all the groups, has returned from a visit to 
the United States of America. Deputy Andrejs Pantelejevs today 
told a news conference that the aim of the visit was to discuss 
the issues of Latvian national security. 
  The delegation was also received by U.S. President Bill 
Clinton and Secretary of State Warren Christopher. It became 
clear during the talks that the United States of America viewed 
the withdrawal of the Russian Army not only as Latvia's internal 
issue, but rather as a problem of all-European and American 
security systems. 
  One of the most complicated issues is the fate of the 
Skrunda 
radar station. Russia has expressed the wish to use it for 
another four years and after that, it will scrap it within 18 
months. In that case, Russia would withdraw all the troops from 
Latvia by 31 August this year. That is the best option which 
Latvia would have to accept, said Deputy Jevgenijs Zoscerinskis. 
Such a compromise would satisfy all the European countries. 
  Deputy Maris Grinblats for his part assessed the results of 
the visit very briefly -- they tried to persuade us that the 
world would be glad if we give in on this issue. 

</TEXT>

