<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> UKRAINE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signing of NPT May Be Deferred </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2701185094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1726 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2701185094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] If the Ukrainian parliament refuses to join the 
treaty on nonproliferation of nuclear weapons [NPT], this may 
lead to a conflict between the republic's legislative and 
executive branches of power. This was said to Interfax by a 
high-ranking official from the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry. 
  Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk called upon the 
parliament to ratify the START I and to sign the treaty on 
nonproliferation on January 24. 
  According to the diplomat, the parliament's plenary session 
may finish on Monday with no decision made on the president's 
proposal. This will mean that the settlement of the issue will 
be deferred for an undetermined period of time. 
  "The Russian president suspended the Supreme Soviet's powers 
and assumed its authority for the period of transition," the 
diplomat remarked. "However, the Ukrainian constitution does not 
mention the right of the president to sign documents on joining 
international treaties in the period of parliamentary 
elections," he emphasized. 
  Deputy Ukrainian Foreign Minister Boris Tarasuk said that 
the 
withdrawal of nuclear military charge from Ukrainian territory 
would continue until the guaranteed terms for their utilization 
expired. 

</TEXT>

