<F P=100> CENTRAL EURASIA </F>
<F P=101> UKRAINE </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Round of Russian-Ukrainian Talks 8 February </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ukraine Expected To Clarify Stance </H4>
<F P=102> LD0702192994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1718 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0702192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia hopes that the talks on the nuclear problem 
to begin in Kiev on Tuesday will clarify all issues pertaining 
to nuclear weapons, leader of the Russian delegation Yuriy 
Dubinin told Interfax. 
  He believes that the Ukrainian parliament's resolution on 
the 
ratification of the START-I treaty, passed on February 4, 1994, 
has many "ambiguous places." It does not say, for instance, 
what percentage of nuclear weapons is to be eliminated. 
  Dubinin said that on November 18, 1993, the Ukrainian 
parliament passed the resolution on the ratification of the 
START-I treaty, according to which only 36% of the 
Ukrainian 
missiles and 42% of the warheads were to be eliminated. 
"This 
goes against both the START-I treaty and the Lisbon agreements. 
It's still unclear whether Ukraine intends to eliminate 
100% 
of the nuclear weapons located on its territory in strict 
accordance with the START-I treaty and the Lisbon protocol," he 
said. 
  According to Dubinin, neither is it clear whether Ukraine 
will join the nonproliferation treaty as a non-nuclear state. 
  Speaking about Ukraine's participation in NATO's Partnership 
for Peace program, he said that Russia is approaching this issue 
calmly. "Russia has already supported the partnership concept. 
Why should Ukraine not join it?" he said. 
<H3>  ...AND UKRAINE WILL SOON JOIN NONPROLIFERATION TREATY, 
AMBASSADOR SAYS </H3>
  Ukraine will be a non-nuclear state and will "shortly" join 
the Nonproliferation Treaty of 1968, the Ukrainian ambassador to 
Russia said. 
  Vladimir Kryzhanovskiy told a news conference in Moscow on 
Monday that the Ukrainian parliament had now approved all the 
points of Article Five of the Lisbon Protocol. "This eliminates 
the main problem, and now everything is ready for joining the 
Treaty on the Nonproliferation of Nuclear Weapons in the 
immediate future," he said. All nuclear arms will be removed 
from Ukraine, he said. 
  Kryzhanovskiy said the Ukrainian legislature had charged the 
government with the exchanging of the START-I ratification 
instruments and instructed it to take more efforts to enter into 
relevant international agreements. 
  The ambassador did not rule out that Ukraine's membership in 
the Nonproliferation Treaty as a non-nuclear state would be 
approved by the present parliament, but said this was most 
likely to be done by the next legislature, to be elected on 
March 27. 
  Commenting on Ukraine's relations with Russia, Kryzhanovskiy 
said there was some friction but that it had set off no 
conflicts between the two nations. As for the idea of the 
incorporation of the Ukrainian autonomous republic of Crimea 
into Russia through a Crimean referendum, he said it would be 
the same as the incorporation of Russia's Kuril Islands into 
Japan on the basis of the results of a referendum by the Kurile 
population. "That's not serious," he said. 
  He said none of the former Soviet republics, including 
Russia, "has given a kopeck" to return Crimean Tatars to Crimea. 

</TEXT>

