<F P=101> ECUADOR </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paredes Cites U.S. Note, Vows Country `Will Not Budge' in Drug Fight </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA2801045294 Paris AFP in Spanish 1907 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2801045294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 27 Jan (AFP) -- The United States has 
confirmed it "will do all that is necessary" to help Ecuador in 
its struggle against drug trafficking, Foreign Minister Diego 
Paredes reported today. He added that it was this fight that 
prompted guerrillas of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of 
Colombia (FARC) to kill 11 Ecuadoran policemen and soldiers. 
  The Ecuadoran official announced that U.S. Secretary of 
State 
Warren Christopher sent a note to Ecuadoran President Sixto 
Duran-Ballen lamenting the death of the 11 uniformed men during 
a FARC ambush. The 11 men were involved in a narcotics 
operation in the area of the Putumayo River, at the Colombian 
border, in December 1993. 
  The U.S. Government "realizes these personnel were killed 
while courageously confronting and combating the threat of 
international drug trafficking, and it values the sacrifices 
made by the national government in this struggle," Christopher 
stated. 
  The note from the United States also "guarantees that its 
government will do everything it can to help Ecuador in this 
effort," Paredes pointed out. 
  The foreign minister added that Ecuador will not budge in 
its 
struggle against drug trafficking and terrorism through the 
application of the law without having second thoughts, and by 
respecting human rights and the country's institutional system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

