<F P=100> EAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> SOUTH KOREA </F>
<H3> <TI>   International Crimes Information Center Established </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901020594 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 29 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901020594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Agency for National Security Planning (NSP), 
the nation's top intelligence agency, has established an 
"information center for international crimes" to tackle 
increasing terror, smuggling and narcotics-related crimes, the 
NSP announced yesterday. 
  The NSP will also open offices to receive reports on such 
crimes in five major cities--Seoul and port cities of Pusan, 
Inchon, Cheju and Masan. 
  An NSP spokesman said that the agency's move is to counter 
effectively the growing number of international organized crimes 
which occurred in the country recently. It is seen as part of 
the agency's effort to suit itself to the changing political and 
economic atmosphere. 
  The NSP will fight against such crimes in the context of 
national security, said the spokesman. 
  The spokesman said the newly established information center 
absorbs the "counter-narcotics information center" initiated 
last June. Last year, the counter-narcotics center collected 
over 300 pieces of drug-related information and distributed them 
to the prosecution, police and foreign intelligence agencies, 
according to the spokesman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

